04629nam a22005655i 9780889207639DE-B159720240306125748.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20061992xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97808892076397 a10.51644/97808892076392doi  a(DE-B1597)667354  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 7aREL0067302bisacsh04a2002231 aHutchinson, Roger, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aProphets, Pastors and Public Choices :bCanadian Churches and the Mackenzie Valley Pipeline Debate /cRoger Hutchinson. 1aWaterloo, Ontario : bWilfrid Laurier University Press, c[2006] 4c©1992  a1 online resource (156 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aComparative Ethics ;v300tFront Matter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tProject North at General Council -- tAcknowledgements -- tIntroduction -- tA Mackenzie Valley Pipeline: From Inevitable Next Step to Public Debate -- tDifferent Stories, Different Definitions of the Problem -- t"Hard Facts" and the Need for a Northern Pipeline -- tAssessing the Consequences -- tCompeting Rights and Conflicting Ways of Life -- tPost-ethical Clarification and Religious Convictions -- tConclusion -- tIndex -- tSR Supplements0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Mackenzie Valley natural gas pipeline debate included many actors. This is the first in-depth study in comparative religious ethics to examine the debate with a particular focus on the role of the Canadian churches. In 1974 twenty-seven of the world’s largest oil and natural gas companies applied for permission to build a pipeline through the Mackenzie Valley to transport Alaskan and northern Canadian gas to large southern markets. Many northern native peoples opposed the proposal and called for a moratorium on major northern development projects until native land claims had been settled. The mainline Canadian Christian churches supported the call for a moratorium and, through the interchurch coalition, Project North, campaigned against the pipeline. However, some native peoples supported the proposal to build the pipeline, and many of the pipeline’s proponents were members of churches that called for a moratorium on the project. This case study in comparative religious ethics, though written from a pro-moratorium stand, attempts to clarify the debate. Conflicting responses to the pipeline proposal are assessed in relation to “hard facts” concerning the need for northern gas in the South, social-scientific findings regarding the impact of the pipeline on native communities, the rights of native peoples to participate in decisions affecting their lives, assumptions about the way of life of non-native people in the South and the role of religious convictions in public choices. This thoroughly researched study reveals the inner workings and influences of the Canadian churches involved and illustrates their commitment on behalf of the northern natives opposed to the project.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aChurch and social problemsxCanada. 0aChurch and social problemszCanada. 0aMackenzie Valley Pipeline (N.W.T.)xEnvironmental aspects. 0aMackenzie Valley Pipeline (N.W.T.)xMoral and ethical aspects. 0aReligion. 4aReligion. 7aRELIGION / Biblical Studies / Prophets.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.51644/978088920763940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780889207639423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780889207639/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-1